title: For Sale:  hi point 9mm 995 +15 round mag
postcontent:
Origin

Developed during the now-defunct 1994 Federal assault weapons ban, the Hi-Point carbine comes with a ten-round magazine that fits into the pistol grip. With the expiration of the federal assault weapons ban in 2004, aftermarket fifteen-round magazines are now also available in most states. The proprietary magazines are only usable with Hi-Point firearms. The pistol-style magazines for the 4095 .40 S&W carbine are fully interchangeable with the Hi-Point .40 S&W pistol. No such compatibility was advertised by Hi-Point regarding the original 995 carbine and the 9mm Hi-Point C-9 pistol; owners of both designs have reported that they are not completely interchangeable. The shorter pistol magazine is not long enough to fit the carbine; however, the longer carbine magazine will fit into the pistol.
Development

Despite its appearance, the Hi-Point carbine was developed for the civilian market and not specifically aimed at police department use. Nevertheless, it has been approved and purchased by a small number of local police departments that cannot easily afford to outfit all of their officers with more expensive long guns.[1]

In the first quarter of 2009, a new model of the 995 carbine was released, the 995TS, which features a new stock and last round hold open. The TS model is slightly more expensive than the "995 Classic". The 4095 model in .40 S&W[2] and the newest model, the Model 4595 in .45 ACP,[3] are available only in the new TS configuration. As of September 2010, the "995 Classic" or "4095 Classic" are no longer featured on the Hi-Point website.[4]
Popularity

The carbine has proven popular, and has established a solid reputation as a plinking rifle or knockabout camp or truck gun.[5] Some 28,000 were made and sold in 1998 alone, and it continues to sell well. After the success of the Model 995, the original 9mm version, the Model 4095 was created in the .40 S&W caliber. It shares much of the success of the Model 995. The newest model, the 4595TS, is poised to share in the success of its smaller-caliber siblings.

Hi-Point has developed a strong following despite the 'ugliness' of their products. A frequently heard epithet refers to the original Hi-Point configuration as "that Planet of the Apes gun." Their guns consistently score high in evaluations run by Gun Tests Magazine.[6] All Hi-Point firearms include a lifetime "no questions asked" warranty that transfers to anyone who purchases a used Hi-Point firearm.[7]

title: For Sale:  Beware The Shady Guys on Here Trying to Buy Guns Without LTC! UPDATED WITH OFFENDERS EMAIL ADRESSES
postcontent:
I regularly use this site to buy and sell firearms within Massachusetts, I've recently had a bunch of inquiries by guys who live in massachusetts and do not have any kind of permit or LTC but want me to sell them my registered firearm for cash and just leave it at that...  I've even spoken on the phone with a few of these guys who last minute admit they do not have an LTC one of them wanted me to meet him Dorchester the same night to make the sale.... Anyone with half a brain can figure out that these guys are just fishing to see who will sell them any firearm without requiring a permit. It's pretty obvious that they have spread the word amongst their buddies on how to get a gun. I wouldn't be writing a post about this if there weren't so many different inquiries on my ads I've had at least 5 different guys try this with me since December. BE CAREFUL with who you meet and try to verify that the person had an LTC before you set a meeting spot. FFL's are a safer bet,  a short phone conversation can tell you a lot about a guy, if it sounds off... don't meet him anywhere. And no matter how much they offer you for your gun just remember that it will still be registered to you after you sell it to them and chances are it will be used to commit a crime and sold around to different people until it becomes evidence. 

UPDATE
Here is a list of email addresses and a phone number that have inquired on my ads since I last posted this and have asked me to do an illegal sale : REDACTED, REDACTED,  REDACTED, REDACTED. This person texted me and asked me to make a cash sale across sate lines with no FFL on a handgun, then got angry when I wouldn't make the deal, I will "*" one of the numbers so he doesn't get any calls: 401-24*-1528.

Why do you need ammo. Because its sold out everywhere? No. You need ammo to go shooting and have fun with our beloved past time. Your guns only hold so much if it was self defense you only need a box or two of corbon defense or HPs.

We have turned from gun loving enthusiasts into hording grandmas on black friday at Toysrus. Buy some ammo and shoot it. They will make more, eventually you can buy cases of it again.

None of my friends will go shooting with me lately. They are sitting on stacks of ammo like the well is gonna run dry. OK for you 5.7 FNH shooters perhaps. but for the rest of us.....stop hording and start shooting already. The government is trying to lull you into becoming a horrible shot because you don't practice anymore. pretty soon those guns are gonna feel too heavy and you will just hand them over for a 3ounce pepper spray that doesn't weigh down your pocket.

OK seriously. I have this ammo for sale and I needs some money.


BTW please view the posting about the fugitive murderer who is trying to buy guns it is a real issue. Its our duty to prevent further tragedy at law abiding gun owners expense.
